GONOCOCCAL DISEASE - USA (03): (CALIFORNIA), INCREASING INCIDENCE
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 17 Apr 2015
Source: North Coast News [edited]
http://www.krcrtv.com/north-coast-news/news/gonorrhea-rates-up-in-humboldt-county/32426484


The Humboldt County Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) [California] is reminding the pubic about the importance of being tested because gonorrhea is on the rise in the county.

Health officials explained that gonorrhea can be successfully treated if caught early and is one of the most common sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) in the U.S. More than 800 000 infections are estimated to occur each year, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

"In Humboldt County, we have seen an increase in cases of both chlamydia and gonorrhea over the last 3 years, especially in the last 3 months," said DHHS Public Health Nurse Eric Gordon.

From 1 Jan through 15 Apr 2015, there have been 82 cases of gonorrhea reported to Public Health, according to DHHS's Epidemiologist Ron Largusa. This trend represents a doubling of cases and rate from 2014 and a 10-fold increase in cases and rate from 2010.

Since 2010, the rate of gonorrhea has increased throughout California, recently reaching its highest point in a 20-year period. Regionally, a number of northern California counties have experienced an increase in the number of gonorrhea cases over the last several years, Gordon said.

The infection is sexually transmitted and can also be spread from an infected pregnant mother to her child during delivery. To reduce the risk of contracting any STD, Gordon recommends that people get tested regularly, know their partner's STD results before starting a new sexual relationship, always use condoms, and minimize anonymous sexual relations and sex with multiple partners.

While as many as 50 percent of gonorrhea cases show no symptoms, those that do most often present themselves in the following ways: For men: A burning sensation when urinating; A white, yellow, or green discharge from the penis; Painful or swollen testicles (although this is less common). For women: Painful or burning sensation when urinating; Increased vaginal discharge; and Vaginal bleeding between periods. Gonorrhea can cause serious and permanent health problems if left untreated, the CDC states. In women, it can cause pelvic inflammatory disease, which can cause complications, including: Formation of scar tissue that blocks fallopian tubes; Ectopic pregnancy (pregnancy outside the womb); Infertility; and Long-term pelvic/abdominal pain.

In men, gonorrhea can cause a painful condition in the tubes attached to the testicles. In rare cases, this may cause a man to be sterile. Although uncommon, untreated gonorrhea can also spread to blood or joints which can be life-threatening, according to the CDC.

One of the most important things that can be done to stop the spread of STDs is to ensure that all sexual partners who may have been exposed to the infection are notified. If someone is not comfortable notifying their partner(s), they can contact Public Health at 707-268-2174 to arrange for anonymous partner notification. For more information and to get tested or treated, call your health care provider. You can also call the Public Health Clinic at 707-268-2108 to schedule an afternoon appointment. Free condoms are available at Public Health's main office, 529 I Street, as well as the Community Wellness Center, 908 Seventh Street, both in Eureka.

[Byline: Maghan Hunt]

