[Gonorrhea rates in the U.S. in 2009 decreased to 98.1 cases per 100 000 population, the lowest rate since recording of gonorrhea rates began. Between 2009 and 2012, the gonorrhea rate increased each year to 106.7 cases per 100 000 population in 2012. In 2013, the gonorrhea rate decreased slightly to 106.1 cases per 100 000 population. However, in 2013, for the 1st time since 2000, the rate of reported gonorrhea cases among men was higher than the rate among women; during 2009-2013, the rate among men increased 20.3 percent, while the rate among women decreased 2.0 percent (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats13/natoverview.htm). The increase among men compared with a decrease among women suggests either increased transmission or increased case ascertainment (e.g., through changes in screening practices such as increased testing and increased extra-genital screening) among MSM (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats13/natoverview.htm).

Because many jurisdictions do not routinely report sex of sex partners or site of infection for gonorrhea cases, trends in gonorrhea rates among men who have sex with men (MSM) cannot be assessed (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats13/gonorrhea.htm). However, The STD Surveillance Network, a network of 12 states and independently funded cities collecting enhanced information on a representative sample of gonorrhea cases reported to the state or city health department from all reporting sources, provides more complete estimates of case characteristics often missing on routine case reports, such as gender of sex partners. From the STD Surveillance Network data, the CDC estimates that in 2012, 26.6 percent of gonorrhea cases were among MSM, 29.4 percent among men who have sex with women (MSW), and 44.1 percent among women. San Francisco County had the highest proportion of estimated MSM cases (87.8 percent), while the lowest proportion of morbidity estimated to be attributed to MSM was found in Jefferson County (Birmingham), Alabama at 10.9 percent (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats12/gonorrhea.htm).

The above news report fails to characterize cases of gonococcal disease in Humboldt County, California as to sex, sex of sex partners or site of infection for gonorrhea cases, which is essential for better targeting of gonorrhea control efforts (http://www.cdc.gov/std/stats13/gonorrhea.htm).

_Neisseria gonorrhoeae_ has progressively developed resistance to each of the antibiotics used for treatment of gonorrhea. Dual therapy with ceftriaxone plus either azithromycin or doxycycline is now the only CDC recommended treatment regimen for gonorrhea. The percentage of isolates that exhibit elevated ceftriaxone minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) increased from 0.1 percent in 2008 to 0.4 percent in 2011, and decreased slightly to 0.3 percent in 2012. The proportion of isolates with elevated azithromycin MICs decreased from 0.5 percent in 2010 to 0.3 percent in 2012.

Humboldt County, with a population of 134 623 in 2010, is located in Northern California on the Pacific Coast, 200 miles north of San Francisco. The county seat is Eureka. - Mod.ML

